<UserId.>107614107210958323343</UserId.><username>Lindsey</username><date>1592198598419</date><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
I've come here since I was a teen and recently visited when back in town. They had a few items at surprisingly good prices (had to double check bc I didn't believe it!). If you're trying to find a gift for the alternative spirituality folks in your life this is a good place to go in and ask questions to find something practical or beautiful or both. It's fun to look at all the books and gifts if you have time to browse. This place was always a metaphysical supply staple in the area. I have never felt uncomfortable being kind of non-alternative-ish in the store - they are respectful and helpful regardless of how you look. Fun selection of incense and candles and symbolic jewelry. Lots of books.</review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
I was pleasantly surprised when my sister brought me to this store. She knows I love exploring New Age stores when I travel, because the closest store to where I live is Atlanta.

This store has a wide selection of goods, from jewelry, tarot cards, books, candles, hygiene products, and more. The store associates were very friendly, which was nice because some stores I've been to they are either pushy or plain rude and domineering. So, to be able to not be hassled but have someone there when I have questions is a breath of fresh air.

We spent a while in there browsing through everything and I would love to come back the next time I make it to the West Coast. ğŸ’–<//review>

< review>
LOVE, LOVE, LOVE this place. It was so nicely laid out with place cards explaining what things were and their metaphysical properties. They are very reasonably priced and staff was very friendly. The (male) owner was a bit gruff but I will chalk that up to a bad day but the long haired brunette was so pleasant n amazing it didn't matter. Most of their jewelry was a bit overpriced BUT I have seen higher prices around the area. They have a great selection of incense, oils, books, cards, candles and clothing. I did not get a reading but I did see the reader they had the day I visited and she may be great for card readings.. I ABSOLUTELY recommend this shop for metaphysical needs n supplies, tho. I LOVEd this store.</review>

< text>
If you want to shop where they treat you as if they ar doing you a favor to shop at their store welll this Management is it.  I asked for something that they did not have 3-4 weeks ago.  I live in the San Fernando Valley and out of nowhere I received a call today that the tarot cards are in.  They can only hold them until the end of today and itia already 3:30pm.  Now, tell me?  Do I own a helicopter?  Give a couple of days notice at least.  They never gave me an approximate time when they would even try to order the cards.   This is totally unexpected on my behalf.  So, I guess I need to drive my SUV in traffic and put $100 in the tank and forget about picking up my kids from school because the Tarot Cards are here today?!!!  They never would have had these if I didn't ask about a particular brand.  If they are that thirsty I don't want the cards.  They will have bad Ju-ju on them anyway.  This is an alleged Spiritual Store.  This guy must think it's Neiman Marcus.  I called the Green Man Store in North Hollywood and they said they would glady hold the cards for a couple of days and it was no big deal.  And their Smudging Feathers were $5 instead of $28.  That's where I will spend my money.  Bye Lady of the Funky Lake.</text>

< text>

<UserId.>103602627235170519908</UserId.><Name>Caroline Kaplan</Name><Date>1618796731069<//Date><rating>1<//rating><text>One star for an overnight stay.  We were looking for a place to stay in the area and called this KOA.  Fatima knew that it was just for a quick overnight (called at 4:15 for a 5:30 arrival). It is 5+ miles of narrow, somewhat twisty roads with some fairly steep hills off the 101.  The sights are set up for utilities on one pole for 2 sites, so one site has to pull all cables, hoses (water and sewer) under their rig to the hook ups.  There is not really a dog area, though there is some areas that you could walk them.  The restrooms are okay.  All of this for a steep overnight total charge of $90+.  This may be a great place for a long stay group camp, etc.  But overnighters, NO.  I do need to mention that there are some pretty views (thanks to the steep hills coming in).</text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>

< Text>
This was our first time camping at a KOA facility.  We were content with our overall experience.  The location was surrounded by beautiful wineries, which we could see from the porch of our cabin (Kingfisher).  The cabin itself was very spacious and cozy with a swing on the front porch.  There was plenty of space between each cabin, allowing our children to play freely.  Each site was equipped with a covered picnic table, a fire pit, a BBQ pit, and a water spigotâ€“making it easy to travel light.  The bathrooms were clean and had hot water!  The staff was friendly, courteous, and flexible.

The property was in good conditionâ€“there were a few improvements that could be made:

1. The swimming pool was not heated as advertisedâ€“we could see the solar system, but the pool was freezing.  The pool / spa was clear, but needed to be skimmed and vacuumed.  The pool furniture was weathered.

2. The Put-Put was not maintained and there was a lot of standing water.  There had been a recent storm, so to compensate for the condition they allowed guests to play for free!

3. The cabin was clean, but there were a lot of spider webs, cobwebs, and spider eggs around the beds.  It looked like there's never been dusting between walls and beds.  We understood there would be insects on our trip, but we weren't expecting them to be our roommates.

4. Not much going on during off season.  So, we missed out on movie nights, breakfast, and other activities that are only scheduled during peak-season.

We have already recommended this facility to family and friends.  We look forward to exploring other KOA facilities!< /Text>

<Rating>3</Rating>< Text>
This RV Park has a lot of facilities including tent areas and lodges. On paper it should be great but I felt it was let down by two things. Firstly and most importantly, the "Summer" directions to the park do not work on a June day at 30 degrees centigrade, you have to follow the "winter" directions which means about a 6 mile detour.  Apparently a bridge "randomly" closes and hence the need to go a different way. This wouldn't be so bad except the office personnel don't know the area well enough to direct you. Once you go the "winter" route its actually well signposted so I'd suggest they simply remove the summer route from their website and tell people to go the other way.   Secondly, the restrooms and showers are OK but not great and I felt they let it down. Otherwise, this could be a good rv Park.</Text>

< Text>
Stopped by here on a Saturday evening with my family. We had a bunch of us in an RV and had a cabin reserved. After we checked in, we drove down to our cabin (cabin 3) and parked the RV next to the cabin like we used to at most other KOA that weve been to over the years. We noticed that there was a sign that said no RVs but we were able to back it in and were not blocking the roadway by any means. My brother went to talk to the office to see if there was a hookup area that we could park the RV since we were in this "no RV" zone... Pamela quickly said "YOU ARE NOT SUPPOSED TO PARK THERE. IT WORRIES ME THAT YOU DROVE RIGHT PAST A SIGN THAT SAYS NO RVS"... my brother left and I went up to talk to her with my mom and she said the same thing... "there is nowhere to park it... we have no spots... etc etc. You need to park it at the train depot and have someone come pick you up". We asked if it was okay if we just left it there while we cooked dinner and ate and then we'd bring it down, but  she said no because it was a fire hazard because it would "take too long to get out of the spot". Keep in mind there is no grass around... just dirt and dried up yellow "grass". This isn't a fire hazard??

Anyways, after we move the RV, my uncle came back and noticed that there was an open spot for RVs with a hookup. It was 8:45-9p so theres a pretty good chance no one was coming. He went to go to talk with Pamela (who we found out was the owner) and the second he walked in with my brother, she immediately started pointing fingers at my brother and says "YOU...WHAT ARE YOU DOING HERE?!  I TOLD YOU THAT YOU HAD TO LEAVE". My uncle kindly asked her to calm down and he wanted to hear the story. He asked if we could bring the RV to the open spot and she quickly said NO WERE COMPLETELY FULL. He told her there was another open spot and she said "NOPE ITS TAKEN AND THERES NO WHERE ELSE FOR YOU TO PARK. WHAT DONT YOU UNDERSTAND ABOUT THAT". He said okay and that we were just going to eat dinner and bring the rest of the family to the RV at the train depot. She quickly responded saying that "only 4 people are allowed in the cabin...no one else." We said we just want to eat dinner... she said we are "no longer welcome here and that we needed to leave". She pointed to different staff members that were in the office to explain to us why, however they seemed to not want back her up. She said that everyone that was not on the 4 person reservation needed to leave immediately.

We sensed that we were not welcome here. We had everyone pack our things and left. She was no longer at the office, but a gentleman (Charles I believe) was there to accept the keys and apologize.

Not only was the owners service completely irrational, but the cabin itself was a complete failure. The outside lights were not working (one light on the stairs and the porch light) AND the hot water wasnt working at all. My wife had to take a cold shower... ice cold.

Unfortunately,  we will not be returning to this location. We were told this is "new management" as of a week ago. If this is what they are going to be like 1 week into owning and running this business, I'm scared to see how it will carry on. Best of luck, KOA. You may be best off disassociating yourself with this campsite.<//Text>

< review>
I tried to call several times to make a reservation and ask a few questions, but no one answered. That's completely fine, but it's just another thing to add to the list. So I made a reservation online, and expected we'd be okay to arrive after hours but could not confirm since I couldn't get ahold of anyone anyway. When we arrived, there was a map for someone elses reservation, but nothing for us. I tried calling the after hours phone number that was posted, but of course, no one answered. We didn't sleep at all because people were drinking and yelling all night. The bathrooms were a complete mess and pretty gross. I would not say our stay was enjoyable in any way. We're not picky though! It's not that we're high maintenance. We just want a nice place to rest our head while on a long road trip. We ended up leaving at 4am because we couldn't sleep anyway. We've stayed at campgrounds all across the country, and this is one of the worst. However, the location, while a little off the beaten path, was really pretty so it deserves the one star for that.<//review>

<text>My family (4 adults & 1 child) spent 4 nights over 4th of July We made our reservation with Pam who was obviously  over worked and could not  multi task if her life depended on it.  It took me 5 phone calls to confirm my reservation when  we asked for a site with shade.  She was somewhat rude and finally I asked her to verify my email after not getting one in 6 days. She had keyed in an incorrect email.
A couple of issues that I reported to the front desk was 1) the dock fell into the pond when a heavy set man walked on it.  It was obviously in need of repair from the  get go.  2) the first step in the pool was so sleek that many people, especially the seniors slipped into the pool. 3) on our last day of our stay the pool was locked at 10AM.  The front desk said that it wouldn't open until noon because the pool needed to be shocked.  There was no sign at the pool.  Why wouldn't they do this job early in the AM so people could swim prior to their check-out at 11? 4) There are no garbage cans at any of the sites.  So many people leave garbage in bags  until they find time to go to the trash bins which are so full and stink from the heat.  Why can't the owner
request additional  garbage pick-ups during holiday weekends?  5) the tent sites are loaded with poison oak and signs should  be posted so that children and/or adults are aware of this potential danger. There were many areas with dead debris in piles  which need to be removed so the sites look attractive. 6) there didn't seem to be very many staff people on site or no special events for a holiday weekend. 7) they should also have a Camper Kitchen for washing pots, etc. We finally found a couple of sinks in the laundry room which we used for this purpose, although we weren't sure this was allowed.
Overall, the one positive comment I have is that the restrooms, were usually clean and the showers were warm although the restrooms  need an up-grade overall.</text><user_name>james garatti<//user_name>< userid>

< Review>
Terrible experience! Trip was canceled short due to lice! We are KOA members and have never had this experience anywhere else.

First, when we arrived at our cabin, the outdoor table and firepit had been rearranged and we were unable to park. We tried to move the firepit and it was full of ash, cigarette butts, and broken glass. I did not want my 2 and 5 year old children to hurt themselves. The cabin was full of dust and cobwebs. We asked to change cabins, however they said it was fully booked and cabins reserved.

They finally sent someone to help return the table and firepit to its original position and clean up the ash and broken glass. The next evening my 5 year old daughter was itching her head, and we found lice. This was summer and the kids had not been in school or interacted with other kids. The lice had to come from the cabin. Our trip ended short and packed and left around 10pm. The nightmare continued with a trip to the pharmacy for lice removal kit and our poor children up past midnight with multiple shampoos and combing.

We tried calling, no one picked up and the mailbox was full. We called and spoke to the night attendant multiple times for a callback and have received no reply. It is such a shame, we where such fans of KOA. We still have reservations this year at other KOAs, however after this experience, there is no way we can go.</Review>

<userid>111845269540774595478< /userid><Name>Noelle Luna< /Name>< time>
1501646895378</time>
<Rating>1</Rating><Review>Our stay 7/28-7/30

We had a group of four families and reserved our spot a few weeks in advance. The one who made the reservations for everyone had been to this KOA with her family a few times before and never had a problem with them. We were given confirmation numbers and tent sites as our reservation date neared. We noticed an issue when the first family arrived. The staff gave away our reservation to a party of ten people. They gave us a few RV spots instead, which were much smaller and much less conducive for tents in the summer heat. Great efforts were made by our people to get the original spots, but there was no apology, not much done to make up for their error. They could have made the party that just came in take our RV spot to honor our original reservation, but that didn't happen. We were given an additional RV site that gave us just enough room to get our tents in the site. The RV sites were on hard, packed ground that bent stakes and made a very hard ground on which to sleep. We were far away from bathrooms, showers, pool...all the amenities you would normally be close to with the tent sites. Thankfully they gave us use of one cabin for restroom use only. We have very small children with little bladders, so this was essential. We should have been offered a discount upon arrival, but we are waiting to have the 10% discount added to our card. There was also a big problem with the place RV's dump their waste. It overflowed the last evening we were there and smelled so very bad. They sprinkled lime on it and addressed an issue with the sewage at the other RV site. Again, no apology. One of the guys drove by and checked on us. He explained that he works on this problem every week. That was pretty troubling that knowing they had a problem like that, and that they put campers with tents on the site anyway with lots of small children. The older lady up front was very blunt and even rude at times. I thought I had clogged the toilet, and called to let them know since we couldn't find a plunger. She demanded to know why the toilet was clogged, so I told her I used the facilities and it wouldn't flush. Then she demanded to know where the key to the cabin was. It was just that she was very rude and kept giving us the run around instead of owning up to their mistakes. The facility as a whole looked run down. The mini golf doesn't really work anymore. The pool was nice. The cabin's toilet was just so low water and they made it use less water so that you had to refill the water in the tank a couple of times just to have a good flush. The grounds were just not as nice as you would expect from a KOA. We are not planning a return trip. We love camping, but their response to us just left us with a bad taste in our mouth...as bad as the smell from the waste and grey water running into our site! So beware. You might have a great experience IF nothing goes wrong. But if there's a misunderstanding in any way, don't expect them to help or care. Sad to say.< /Review><Pics>None</Pics>< response>
None</response>

<date>1563769777140<//date><Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
There's several Alberto's throughout Los Angeles, but this is the only one I keep coming back to. The place is clean, food is good, and the prices are incredibly low. The reason i give it 4 stars, is due to the sometimes difficulty in finding parking. Their lot fits 8-10 cars... But feels like it can only accommodate 2. But other than that, if your hungry and in the area... This is the one place I recommend. I've had everything on the menu, the only item I didn't like was the Fish Taco. So, check it out this hidden tiny foodie joint for yourself. Believe me, you won't regret it!
*Best item on the menu: Carne Asada Tostada ğŸ˜‹<//text>

< text>
Maximum capacity is about 30 people. Each table hold 4 people. The service was reasonable not bad but not a five star restaurant.
I ordered the super fries and let me tell you its a huge portion of food. I came in famished but even that said I was not able to finish my food.
The chunks of beef on the fries was so juicy and packed with a lot of flavor maybe due to the spices. DONT CHANGE THE RECIPE!

I also notice a couple of tables dirty it makes sense if Alberts was busy but not a lot of guest were at the store so there is no excuse.

Reminder. Tables should get wiped down after guest are done dinning in.

I recommend coming on down and give their food a try you wonâ€™t be disappointed unless the tables are dirty but that should not sway you away from dinning in use your voice and ask the wonderful employees.
ps. df< /text>
